05444nam a22009015i 9780812293654DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)992526919  a97808122936547 a10.9783/97808122936542doi  a(DE-B1597)481198  a(OCoLC)972292173  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1064.U5bS255 2017 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a305.2609732231 aSamuel, Lawrence R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAging in America :bA Cultural History /cLawrence R. Samuel. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Old in the Country of the Young -- t2. The De-Aging of America -- t3. The Aging of Aquarius -- t4. The Perpetual Adolescent -- t5. The Silver Tsunami -- t6. Raging Against Aging -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAging is a preoccupation shared by beauty bloggers, serious journalists, scientists, doctors, celebrities—arguably all of adult America, given the pervasiveness of the crusade against it in popular culture and the media. We take our youth-oriented culture as a given but, as Lawrence R. Samuel argues, this was not always the case. Old age was revered in early America, in part because it was so rare. Indeed, it was not until the 1960s, according to Samuel, that the story of aging in America became the one we are most familiar with today: aging is a disease that science will one day cure, and in the meantime, signs of aging should be prevented, masked, and treated as a source of shame.By tracing the story of aging in the United States over the course of the last half century, Samuel vividly demonstrates the ways in which getting older tangibly contradicts the prevailing social values and attitudes of our youth-obsessed culture. As a result, tens of millions of adults approaching their sixties and seventies in this decade do not know how to age, as they were never prepared to do so.Despite recent trends that suggest a more positive outlook, getting old is still viewed in terms of physical and cognitive decline, resulting in discrimination in the workplace and marginalization in social life. Samuels concludes Aging in America by exhorting his fellow baby boomers to use their economic clout and sheer numbers to change the narrative of aging in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aAgingxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aAgingxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aAgingxSocial aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aAgingxSocial aspectsxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aAgingxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAgingxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aAgingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAgingzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aOlder peoplezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aOlder peoplezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aPopulation agingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopulation agingzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 4aAmerican History. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z